[[Category:Lists of mountains|Tallest]] [[Category:Solar System]] [[Category:Lists of superlatives in astronomy|Mountains, tallest in the Solar System]] [[Category:Lists of extraterrestrial mountains|Solar System]] [[Category:Lists of highest points|Solar System]]

{{main|List of mountain peaks of Canada}}
{{see also|List of the highest major summits of Canada|List of the most isolated major summits of Canada}} 

[[Image:Mount Logan.jpg|thumb|400px|[[Mount Logan]] in the [[Saint Elias Mountains]] of [[Yukon]] is the [[topographic elevation|highest]] [[summit (topography)|peak]] of [[Canada]].]]

The following sortable table comprises the '''150 [[Topographic prominence|most topographically prominent]] [[Summit|mountain peaks]] of [[Canada]]'''.

The [[summit]] of a mountain or hill may be measured in three principal ways:
#The [[Elevation|topographic elevation]] of a summit measures the height of the summit above a [[Geoid|geodetic sea level]].<ref name=range>If the elevation or prominence of a summit is calculated as a range of values, the [[arithmetic mean]] is shown.</ref>
#The [[topographic prominence]] of a summit is a measure of how high the summit rises above its surroundings.<ref name=prominence>The [[topographic prominence]] of a summit is the [[Elevation|topographic elevation]] difference between the summit and its [[Topographic prominence#Definitions|highest or key col to a higher summit]].  The summit may be near its key col or quite far away.  The key col for [[Denali]] in [[Alaska]] is the [[Isthmus of Rivas]] in [[Nicaragua]], {{convert|7642|km|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}} away.</ref><ref name=range/>
#The [[topographic isolation]] (or radius of dominance) of a summit measures how far the summit lies from its nearest point of equal elevation.<ref name=isolation>The [[topographic isolation]] of a summit is the [[great-circle distance]] to its nearest point of equal elevation.</ref>

[[Mount Logan]] exceeds {{convert|5000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}} of topographic prominence.  Five peaks of Canada exceed {{convert|3000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}}, 11 exceed {{convert|2500|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}}, 41 exceed {{convert|2000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}}, and [[List of Ultras of Canada|143 ultra-prominent summits exceed {{convert|1500|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}} of topographic prominence]].

__TOC__{{clear}}

==Most prominent summits==
{{GeoGroup|section=Most prominent summits}}
{{see also|List of the ultra-prominent summits of Canada}}
Of these 150 most prominent summits of Canada, 108 are located in British Columbia, 20 in Yukon, 16 in Nunavut, ten in Alberta, and one in the Northwest Territories.  Three of these summits lie on the British Columbia-Alberta border and two lie on the British Columbia-Yukon border.  Four of these summits lie on the international Yukon-Alaska border and four lie on the international British Columbia-Alaska border.
{{clear}}
