{{short description|Average level of the spring high tides over a fairly long period of time}}
The '''mean high water springs (MHWS)''' is the highest level that [[spring tide]]s reach on the average over a period of time (often 19 years). The height of mean high water springs is the average throughout the year (when the average maximum [[declination]] of the [[moon]] is 23.5°) of two successive [[high water]]s during those periods of 24 hours when the range of the tide is at its greatest.<ref>http://www.ntslf.org/tgi/definitions</ref> 

This level is generally close to being the "[[high water mark]]" where debris accumulates on the shore annually.

