[[Category:Mass spectrometry]]
[[Category:Ions]]

[[File:Oruanui Loc1287 u3 25-33cm.jpg|thumb|Volcanic ash aggregates ([[accretionary lapilli]]) in [[ignimbrite]] from the [[Oruanui eruption]] of Taupo volcano, New Zealand.]] '''Volcanic ash aggregation''' occurs when particles of [[volcanic ash]] collide and stick together during transport. This process modifies the [[Particle-size distribution|size distribution]] of airborne particles, which affects both atmospheric dispersal and fallout patterns on the ground. Aggregation also impacts the dynamics of [[Eruption column|volcanic plumes]], [[Pyroclastic flow|pyroclastic density currents]], and their associated [[Volcanic ash and aviation safety|hazards]].
== Numerical models == There are two main approaches to include the effects of ash aggregation in numerical models of ash injection and dispersal. One is to initialize the model with an aggregated [[Particle-size distribution|grain size distribution]], by moving fractions of the erupted mass into larger size bins (for example, the Cornell model<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cornell|first=W|last2=Carey|first2=S|last3=Sigurdsson|first3=H|year=1983|title=Computer simulation of transport and deposition of the campanian Y-5 ash|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037702738390063X|journal=Journal of Volcanology and Geothermal Research|volume=17|pages=89–109|via=|bibcode=1983JVGR...17...89C|doi=10.1016/0377-0273(83)90063-X}}</ref>). A second approach is a full theoretical description of aggregate growth through time, based on the [[Smoluchowski coagulation equation]]. Several methods exist to deal with&nbsp;this equation, including continuous and discrete methods. Continuous methods use the [[Method of moments (statistics)|method of moments]] to track the evolution of a continuous [[Particle-size distribution|grain size distribution]], typically represented by a mean and standard deviation<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Veitch|first=G|last2=Woods|first2=AW|year=2001|title=Particle aggregation in volcanic eruption columns|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1029/2000JB900343/abstract|journal=Journal of Geophysical Research: Solid Earth|volume=106|pages=26425–26441|via=|doi=10.1029/2000JB900343|bibcode=2001JGR...10626425V}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=de' Michieli Vitturi|first=M|last2=Neri|first2=A|last3=Barsotti|first3=S|year=2015|title=PLUME-MoM 1.0: A new integral model of volcanic plumes based on the method of moments|url=http://www.geosci-model-dev.net/8/2447/2015/|journal=Geoscientific Model Development|volume=8|issue=8|pages=2447–2463|via=|bibcode=2015GMD.....8.2447D|doi=10.5194/gmd-8-2447-2015}}</ref>. In contrast, discrete methods use a discretized (binned) grain size distribution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Costa|first=A|last2=Folch|first2=A|last3=Macedonio|first3=G|year=2010|title=A model for wet aggregation of ash particles in volcanic plumes and clouds: 1. Theoretical formulation|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1029/2009JB007175/full|journal=Journal of Geophysical Research: Solid Earth|volume=115|pages=B09201|doi=10.1029/2009JB007175|via=|bibcode=2010JGRB..115.9201C}}</ref> Areas of uncertainty in the numerical schemes include parameterization of the particle sticking efficiency, timescales over which aggregation occurs, and the fraction of erupted mass participating in the aggregation process.&nbsp;
